<emphasis box="[288,481,1998,2024]" italics="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="71">Cheilosia lucida</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Barkalov A. V. &amp; Cheng X. - Y." box="[489,786,1998,2024]" pageId="70" pageNumber="71" pagination="313 - 321" refId="ref48523" refString="Barkalov A. V. &amp; Cheng X. - Y. 1998. New species and new records of hover-flies of the genus Cheilosia Mg. from China (Diptera: Syrphidae). Zoosystematica Rossica 7: 313 - 321." type="journal article" year="1998">Barkalov &amp; Cheng, 1998</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, ♂ (CSCA); lateral view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="71.[189,324,265,291]" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="71.[189,1398,309,368]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[664,752,309,335]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">macula</emphasis>
’ and means ‘spotted’, referring to the lateral greyish maculae of abdominal tergites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
